const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How does progressive taxation work in Italy?',
    answer: 'Italy uses a progressive (a scaglioni) income tax system. This means that each tax bracket only applies to the portion of income that falls within it &mdash; not to your entire income. For example, if you earn &euro;35,000, you pay 23% on the first &euro;28,000 and 35% only on the remaining &euro;7,000. Your effective (average) tax rate will always be lower than the marginal rate of your highest bracket. This system is mandated by Article 53 of the Italian Constitution, which requires taxation to be proportional to one\'s ability to pay.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between effective tax rate and marginal tax rate?',
    answer: 'The <strong>marginal rate</strong> (aliquota marginale) is the tax rate applied to the last euro you earn &mdash; i.e., the rate of the bracket your income falls into. The <strong>effective rate</strong> (aliquota media/effettiva) is the total IRPEF divided by your total taxable income, expressed as a percentage. For instance, on &euro;40,000 taxable income the marginal rate is 35%, but the effective rate is about 26.2%. The effective rate always reflects the blended impact of all lower brackets.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Has the number of IRPEF brackets changed recently?',
    answer: 'Yes. Until 2023, Italy had four IRPEF brackets (23%, 25%, 35%, 43%). Starting from 2024, the government merged the first two brackets into a single 23% bracket covering income up to &euro;28,000. This change was made permanent (structural) from 2025 onward. The result is three brackets: 23% up to &euro;28,000, 35% from &euro;28,001 to &euro;50,000, and 43% above &euro;50,000. The reform benefits taxpayers with income between &euro;15,001 and &euro;28,000, who previously paid 25% on part of their income.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How is IRPEF calculated on the tredicesima (13th month pay)?',
    answer: 'The <strong>tredicesima</strong> (13th-month salary) is treated as ordinary employment income for IRPEF purposes. Your employer calculates the IRPEF withholding on the tredicesima by considering your cumulative annual income up to that point. Because the tredicesima is typically paid in December, it is added to your year-to-date earnings, and the progressive IRPEF rates apply to the total. In practice, the marginal rate on your tredicesima is often higher than your average monthly rate because it pushes your cumulative income further into a higher bracket. For example, if your monthly salary keeps you within the 23% bracket but the tredicesima pushes you past &euro;28,000, the portion above &euro;28,000 is taxed at 35%. Note that the employment income deduction (detrazione per lavoro dipendente) is already fully accounted for in the 12 regular months, so the tredicesima typically has <strong>no additional deduction</strong> applied, resulting in a higher effective tax rate on that payment.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does IRPEF work for dual-income households in Italy?',
    answer: 'Italy does not offer joint taxation for married couples or partners. IRPEF is calculated <strong>individually</strong> &mdash; each spouse or partner files and is taxed on their own income. There is no option to file jointly or split income between partners, as exists in some other countries (e.g., the German Ehegattensplitting or the US joint return). However, tax deductions for dependent family members (detrazioni per carichi di famiglia) can be allocated between partners. For example, if one spouse earns significantly more than the other, the higher earner can claim 100% of the deductions for dependent children, or the couple can split them 50/50. Since each person is taxed individually, a household where two people each earn &euro;30,000 will pay less total IRPEF than a household where one person earns &euro;60,000, because the progressive brackets are applied separately to each income.',
  },
];
